by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":54,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel was born in 1170, in Lancashire, England. She married Sir Helyas de Featherstone of Featherstonehalg about 1200, in Bleasdale, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1254, in Preston, Lancashire, England, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1170–1254":"1170–1254","1168–1225":"1168–1225","1199–Male":"1199–Surnud","1202–1243":"1202–1243","1213–1272":"1213–1272","1272":"1272","1170":"1170","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1224":"1224","1213":"1213","1202":"1202","1168":"1168","1199":"1199","1243":"1243","1254":"1254","about 1202":"umbes 1202","about 1213":"umbes 1213","about 1200":"umbes 1200","Bleasdale, Lancashire, England":"Bleasdale, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Preston, Lancashire, England":"Preston, Lancashire, England","Featherstone Castle, Featherstone, Northumberland, England":"Featherstone, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Featherstone, Northumberland, England":"Featherstone, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1170–1254":"1170–1254","1168–1225":"1168–1225","1199–Male":"1199–Kuollut","1202–1243":"1202–1243","1